National Transportation Safety Board
Aviation Accident Final Report
Location: Lancaster, PA
Accident Number: NYC05CA047
Date & Time: 02/01/2005, 1426 EST
Registration: N59MB
Aircraft: Bell 206B
Aircraft Damage: Substantial
Defining Event:
Injuries: 1 None
Flight Conducted Under: Part 91: General Aviation - Personal
 Analysis As the pilot increased collective to transition to a hover, the helicopter immediately rolled over onto its right side.
The pilot added that the helicopter was positioned into the direct sunlight, and he experienced "dazzling sunlight" being reflected from surrounding snow banks.
The pilot did not report any mechanical difficulties with the helicopter.
Probable Cause and Findings The National Transportation Safety Board determines the probable cause(s) of this accident to be: The pilot's loss of lateral control while attempting to transition to a hover from the ground.
A factor was the bright sunlight conditions.
Findings Occurrence #1: LOSS OF CONTROL - ON GROUND/WATER Phase of Operation: TAKEOFF Findings 1.
(F) LIGHT CONDITION - SUNGLARE 2.
(C) AIRCRAFT CONTROL - NOT MAINTAINED - PILOT IN COMMAND ---------- Occurrence #2: IN FLIGHT COLLISION WITH TERRAIN/WATER Phase of Operation: DESCENT - UNCONTROLLED Findings 3.
